## Their Advice for Aspiring Bitcoin Artists

<blockquote class="relative border-l-4 border-secondary pl-6 my-8 italic text-lg text-base-content/80">
  <span class="absolute -left-3 -top-2 text-5xl text-secondary/20">"</span>
  Don't go too fast. Do it because you really believe in it... Bitcoin goes really in waves. That makes it sometimes hard if you really would like to live from the art.
</blockquote>

Their advice is refreshingly honest. Here's what they learned after 5 years:

### 1. Keep Your Day Job (Seriously)

Don't quit your job to become a Bitcoin artist. The market is too cyclical. Erik and Mark still work full-time - Erik in IT, Mark in mental health. Bitcoin Design is their side project, and that's exactly how they like it.

### 2. Expect Waves

Bitcoin interest comes in waves. Sometimes nobody's interested for months. Then everyone's enthusiastic. If you need consistent income, this isn't it.

### 3. Do It for Conviction, Not Quick Money

If you're in it to get rich, you'll burn out during the slow periods. They do it because they believe in Bitcoin and enjoy working together as family.

### 4. Time Commitment Varies Wildly

More work during exhibitions and busy periods. Less when life gets busy. Don't plan on consistent hours.

### 5. Start with Family or Friends

Working with people you trust makes the journey better. Their mom wasn't into Bitcoin at first, but she had the skills. Now she's a fan.

**The Mom Update:** Remember the mom who wasn't into Bitcoin? "She's also a fan right now. We made her a fan." Mission accomplished.

### 6. Physical Exhibitions Matter

Most sales happen where people can feel the product. Online photos don't convey the impact of a 10kg bronze Bitcoin.

### Their Dream

<blockquote class="relative border-l-4 border-warning pl-6 my-8 italic text-lg text-base-content/80">
  <span class="absolute -left-3 -top-2 text-5xl text-warning/20">"</span>
  Maybe El Salvador or something... they would like to have a really big sculpture somewhere over there. That would be nice.
</blockquote>

They don't talk about galleries in New York or million-dollar sales. They want to see their sculpture in El Salvador, where Bitcoin is actually money. Maybe gift one to Bukele. Maybe have it in a public square.

Simple dreams from guys who aren't trying to be the next Banksy.

---

## Conclusion: Is Bitcoin Art Worth It?

Erik and Mark aren't trying to revolutionize art. They're not quitting their jobs tomorrow. They're not moving to Bitcoin Beach.

They're just two brothers who took their mom's challenge, learned bronze casting, and now make sculptures that let people hold something that can't be held.

### The Real Takeaway for Aspiring Bitcoin Artists

**If you want to get rich quick:** This isn't it. 30-40 pieces in 5 years won't pay your rent.

**If you want to work with conviction:** Bitcoin art can be incredibly fulfilling. You're making something you believe in, with people you trust.

**If you need stability:** Keep your day job. Bitcoin markets are cyclical. Your art income will fluctuate wildly.

**If you want balance:** This is actually perfect. Work your job, make art on the side, don't burn out chasing viral success.

### What They Really Want

<blockquote class="relative border-l-4 border-accent pl-6 my-8 italic text-lg text-base-content/80">
  <span class="absolute -left-3 -top-2 text-5xl text-accent/20">"</span>
  Bitcoin is getting more normalized... but hopefully it will be more used in the future, not just kept and sold later.
</blockquote>

They want Bitcoin to be money, not just digital gold. They want miners to eat (someone gets it). They want transactions happening, not just HODLing.

And they're doing their part, one bronze sculpture at a time, between psychology sessions and coding sprints.

In a world of digital everything, they're making Bitcoin you can drop on your foot. And it would hurt. Because it's 10 fucking kilograms of bronze.

